description: From Middle English hyghwhele; also highwale (1500s) or highawe (1600s). Rarely attested before the sixteenth century, making the original form difficult to trace. Probably imitative of the bird's cry; compare yaffle (“green woodpecker”). Possibly influenced by witwall, woodwall.

entries.meaning: (UK, regional) A lesser spotted woodpecker, Dryobates minor.
(UK, regional) A European green woodpecker, Picus viridis.
(UK, regional, archaic) A blue tit, Cyanistes caeruleus.
